ngs":["English: habitational name from Tilney (Norfolk), which derives its name from the Old English personal name <i>Tila</i>, <i>Tilla</i> (genitive <i>Tilan</i>, <i>Tillan</i>) + Old English <i>ēg</i> ‘island’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Frederick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic origin, from <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced into Britain by them, but did not survive long. Modern use in Britain dates from the 17th century, and it became more frequent in the 18th among followers of the Elector of Hanover, who in  1714  became  George I  of England. It was reinforced by the vogue for Germanic names in Victorian times."],"variants":[{"name":"Frederic","meanings":["From German.  See  <b>Friedrich</b>    and <b>Frederick</b> ."]},{"name":"Fredrick","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic origin, from <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced into Britain by them, but did not survive long. Modern use in Britain dates from the 17th century, and it became more frequent in the 18th among followers of the Elector of Hanover, who in  1714  became  George I  of England. It was reinforced by the vogue for Germanic names in Victorian times."]},{"name":"Fredric","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic origin, from <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced into Britain by them, but did not survive long. Modern use in Britain dates from the 17th century, and it became more frequent in the 18th among followers of the Elector of Hanover, who in  1714  became  George I  of England. It was reinforced by the vogue for Germanic names in Victorian times."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":10,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":23,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":32,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Frederick Tilney was born in 1305, in Boston, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Philip De Tilney, was 34 and his mother, Mochete, was 30. He married Margaret Rocheford. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1360, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1305–1360":"1305–1360","1300–1405":"1300–1405","1309–1336":"1309–1336","1335–1394":"1335–1394","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1360–1436":"1360–1436","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1275":"1275","1385":"1385","Abt 1335":"umbes 1335","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1436":"1436","1336":"1336","1324":"1324","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","about 1336":"umbes 1336","1453":"1453","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1405":"1405","Boston, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England","Boston, Lestrs, Boston, Lincoln, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":